ce:section.ce:para:
The nanocomposite GQDs@Fe3O4/MIP was utilized as a sensitive probe for the detection of ceftazidime in milk samples. The concentration found in milk samples were between not detectable and 0.50 μg L−1. The accuracy of the optosensor using nanocomposite GQDs@Fe3O4/MIP probe was appraised by the determination of ceftazidime in spiked milk samples at various concentrations (0.20, 1.0, 2.0 and 5.0 μg L−1). The accuracy was determined as regards to relative recovery (%) which was obtained from the following equation: Relative recovery (%) = (CFound-CSample/CAdded) ×100. where, CFound is the analyte concentration found in a spiked sample, CSample is the analyte concentration in a real milk and CAdded is the standard concentration spiked in a milk. Recovery was satisfactory, falling within the range of 90.7–99.2% with a RSDs lower than 6% (Table 1
                        ). Further, the results obtained by the developed optosensor was also compared with an HPLC technique. Standard ceftazidime solutions were spiked in milk samples and then extracted as described in Section 2.7. Since the sensitivity of the HPLC method was lower than the sensitivity of the optosensor, the ceftazidime extracted from milk samples was diluted ten times before analysis with the optosensor and without dilution before analysis by HPLC. As can be seen in Fig. 7
                        A, the results produced by the developed optosensor agreed well with the results from HPLC method with a good coefficient of determination of 0.9989. The HPLC chromatograms of ceftazidime detected in spiked milk samples are shown in Fig. 7B. These results indicated that the fabricated optosensor provides an accurate method of determining ceftazidime in milk samples.
